    "verifyText": {
      "id": "lf_help_0",
      "value": "This tool compares two bond investments: buying a bond at a substantial discount to par value and receiving no coupon (a zero-coupon bond ), and buying a bond with a coupon. Rates of return are provided for two periods: 1) the remaining term to maturity ) (your yield to maturity ) and 2) the number of months until you sell the bonds."
    }
  },
  {
    "verifyText": {
      "id": "lf_help_1",
      "value": "Depending on the types of bonds being compared, the taxes applied to coupon payments will vary. Treasury securities are exempt from state income taxes. Municipal bonds are exempt from federal income taxes. In some cases, muni bonds are also exempt from state income taxes."
    }
  },
  {
    "verifyText": {
      "id": "lf_help_2",
      "value": "With a zero-coupon bond, you must report imputed interest as income. As a result, your after-tax rate of return on a zero-coupon bond may be lower."
    }
