    "verifyText": {
      "id": "lf-help-tooltip-text",
      "value": "A zero-coupon bond is sold at a large discount to par value that pays no coupon interest. As the bond approaches its maturity date, the price of the bond rises towards par value. This appreciation of a zero-coupon bond is called imputed interest. The IRS requires you to report imputed interest as taxable income unless you have earned it on a tax-exempt bond."
